title: Show HN: Mockup – A UI/UX Sketching App for iPad Got a Major Update
text:
Hey HN,

I’d like to introduce, our app, Mockup - the ideal design tool for sketching and creating blueprints for apps or web designs.

One of my end goals is to make the design process easy and intuitive and that's exactly what Mockup does with its 45+ templates, flexible canvas, Library to save your elements, and a range of other attributes. With features like the Lasso tool, text and image insertion, 4000 symbols from Apple's SF Symbols library, and a customizable grid, your design possibilities are endless.

And, the best part? I've just released a brand new update, packed with features suggested by our users to make the design experience even better like arrange objects, copy & paste, and an enhanced toolbar. Not to mention, users can now publish their elements to the community and access elements created by others as well as create UI for TV apps with the highly requested newly added TV template.

I can't wait for you to try it out!

Ask HN: Separate Up and Down Vote Count
text:
I've been noticing an increasing trend on my comments where the "score" oscillates rapidly up and down by a few points with a slight upward trend over time. From observing it, it looks like the comment is getting 100s of ratings but might only have a net score of 20.

A post with 20 ratings and a score of 20 probably signals something different than a post with 1000 ratings and a score of 20. One signals that fewer people were interested in the comment but those who are were generally supportive of it while the other signals many people were interested in the comment but they were split in their opinions of it.

It would be cool to see these numbers for comments!

text: Email writing is a notorious pain in every dev's butt. I wrote a small tool that allows for live previewing of your HTML mail with handlebars. You can add in test data to mimick e.g. your nodemailer setup. You can also send a testmail to your mailtrap account if you need some extra info, or just want to see how it looks in a mailclient.

Ask HN: Are Scrum-Masters Useful / Worth a Full-Time Salary?
text:
Our company has gone on a spree of hiring Scrum-Masters for virtually every team, and it seems like this role adds little to no value to the teams or company.

The SM's all seem to work a few hours at most a day, most of which is running a 15-minute Daily Standup that typically goes 30 minutes (yeah they're not even running standup right).

Is this common? Am I crazy to think that this is maybe a perfect low-hanging fruit for ChatGPT to essentially replace in the next few years?
